04106nam a22005415i 9780773553972DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20182018xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735539727 a10.1515/97807735539722doi  a(DE-B1597)657115  a(OCoLC)1055161007  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aE78.Q3bL69 2018eb 7aHIS0060102bisacsh04a971.4004/972231 aLozier, Jean-François, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFlesh Reborn :bThe Saint Lawrence Valley Mission Settlements through the Seventeenth Century /cJean-François Lozier. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource :b6 maps, 11 figures  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMcGill-Queen's French Atlantic Worlds Series ;v200tFront Matter -- tContents -- tFigures -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tSowing Seeds -- tFriends and Brothers -- tThe Enemy’s Arms -- tPromised Lands -- tFlesh Born Again -- tAgainst their Own -- tIn their Place -- tThe Tree of Peace -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Saint Lawrence valley, connecting the Great Lakes to the Atlantic, was a crucible of community in the seventeenth century. While the details of how this region emerged as the heartland of French colonial society have been thoroughly outlined by historians, much remains unknown or misunderstood about how it also witnessed the formation of a string of distinct Indigenous communities, several of which persist to this day. Drawing on a range of ethnohistorical sources, Flesh Reborn reconstructs the early history of seventeenth-century mission settlements and of their Algonquin, Innu, Wendat, Iroquois, and Wabanaki founders. Far from straightforward byproducts of colonialist ambitions, these communities arose out of an entanglement of armed conflict, diplomacy, migration, subsistence patterns, religion, kinship, leadership, community-building, and identity formation. The violence and trauma of war, even as it tore populations apart and from their ancestral lands, brought together a great human diversity. By foregrounding Indigenous mission settlements of the Saint Lawrence valley, Flesh Reborn challenges conventional histories of New France and early Canada. It is a comprehensive examination of the foundation of these communities and reveals the fundamental ways they, in turn, shaped the course of war and peace in the region.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aIndians of North AmericazSaint Lawrence River ValleyxGovernment relationsy17th century. 0aIndians of North AmericazSaint Lawrence River ValleyxHistoryy17th century. 7aHISTORY / Canada / Pre-Confederation (to 1867).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311127363108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2018z978311127598740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780773553972?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773553972423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773553972/original  a978-3-11-127363-1  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  a978-3-11-127598-7  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles